  "nodes": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "name": "But \\[ \\dot \\omega_E = - \\frac{2\\pi}{T^2} = -\\omega_E \\frac{\\dot T}{T}\\] where \\(\\dot T = dT/dt\\), so the rate of increase of distance between Earth and Moon is \\[ \\frac{dR}{dt} = - \\frac{2I}{\\mu R} \\left( \\frac{\\omega_E}{\\omega_M} \\right) \\cdot \\left( \\frac{\\dot T}{T} \\right) \\]",
      "alias": "",
      "type": "Event"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "name": "From historical observations, the rate at which our day in lengthening is about \\(2ms\\) per century \\( = 2 \\times 10^{-5} \\) seconds per year.",
      "alias": "",
      "type": "Event"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "name": "Mass of the Earth",
      "alias": "",
      "type": "Thing"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "name": "Mass of the Moon",
      "alias": "",
      "type": "Thing"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "name": "Moment of Inertia of the Earth",
      "alias": "",
      "type": "Thing"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "name": "Radius of the Moon",
      "alias": "",
      "type": "Thing"
    },
    {
      "id": 7,
      "name": "Rate of distance (increase) \\( = 0.036\\) m/year, or 3.6 centimetres per year. (note) This can be measured by laser reflection off the Moon.",
      "alias": "",
      "type": "Event"
    },
    {
      "id": 8,
      "name": "Rate of distance (increase) \\[   \\frac{dR}{dt} = \\frac{2 \\times 8.1 \\times 10^{37}}{7.4 \\times 10^{22} \\times 3.8 \\times 10^8} \\left( \\frac{27}{1} \\times \\frac{2 \\times 10^{-5}}{3600 \\times 24} \\right) \\] as the moon's orbit is about 27 days and the number of seconds in a day is about \\(60 \\times 60 \\times 24\\).",
      "alias": "",
      "type": "Event",
      "tooltip": "There are some approximations and measurement uncertainties,"
    },
    {
      "id": 9,
      "name": "Substuting from Kepler's law \\[ I\\dot\\omega_E +  \\frac{1}{2}\\mu R\\omega_M \\frac{dR}{dt}  = 0 \\]",
      "alias": "",
      "type": "Event"
    },
    {
      "id": 10,
      "name": "The tides raised by the Moon are dragged ahead of the line of centres due to the \"friction\" of the contintental ocean floors. This means the Moon exerts a braking torque on the Earth. The loss of spin angular momentum is transferred to the Moon's orbital momentum.",
      "alias": "",
      "type": "Thing"
    },
    {
      "id": 11,
      "name": "The total angular momentum \\(L\\) of the Earth-Moon system is approximately constant. \\[ L_{\\rm TOT} = I\\omega_{\\rm earth} + \\mu R^2 \\omega_{\\rm moon} \\] where \\(\\mu\\) is the reduced mass \\[ \\mu = \\frac{mM}{m+M} = 7.4 \\times 10^{22} kg \\]",
      "alias": "",
      "type": "Event"
    },
    {
      "id": 12,
      "name": "To invoke the conservation of momentum, differentiate %wrt time \\(d/dt = 0\\) \\[ 0 = I\\dot\\omega_E + \\frac{1}{2}\\mu R^{\\frac{1}{2}} \\sqrt{GM} \\frac{dR}{dt}\\]",
      "alias": "",
      "type": "Event"
    },
    {
      "id": 13,
      "name": "\\( I = 8.1 \\times 10^{37} kgm^2\\)",
      "alias": "",
      "type": "Concept"
    },
    {
      "id": 14,
      "name": "\\( M = 6 \\times 10^{24} kg\\)",
      "alias": "",
      "type": "Concept"
    },
    {
      "id": 15,
      "name": "\\( R = 3.8 \\times 10^{8} m\\)",
      "alias": "",
      "type": "Concept"
    },
    {
      "id": 16,
      "name": "\\( m = 7.4 \\times 10^{22} kg\\)",
      "alias": "",
      "type": "Concept"
    },
    {
      "id": 17,
      "name": "\\(R\\) and \\(\\omega\\) are related by Kepler's Law: \\[ \\omega_{\\rm Moon}^2 R^3 = GM\\] thus the total angular momentum is \\[ L_{\\rm tot} = I \\omega_E + \\mu R^{\\frac{1}{2}} \\sqrt{GM} \\]",
      "alias": "",
      "type": "Event"
    },
    {
      "id": 18,
      "name": "with respect to",
      "alias": "",
      "type": "Concept"
    },
    {
      "id": 19,
      "name": "wrt",
      "alias": "",
      "type": "Event"
    }
  ],
